CS-4760 Project 5 — Test Plan
==============================
Run all tests on opsys.cs.umsl.edu after a clean build.
Each test lists the command, what to observe, and what pass/fail looks like.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T01  Clean build — no warnings
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Command:
    make clean && make

Pass:  Both executables built. Zero compiler warnings or errors.
Fail:  Any "error:" or "warning:" line in gcc output.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T02  Help flag
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Command:
    ./oss -h

Pass:  Prints usage line mentioning [-h] [-n] [-s] [-t] [-i] [-f].
       Exits 0. No IPC created (ipcs -m / ipcs -q unchanged).
Fail:  Crash, hang, or IPC created.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T03  Minimal run — basic message flow and clean exit
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Command:
    ./oss -n 3 -s 2 -t 3 -f t03.log

Pass:
  - Forks exactly 3 workers (P0, P1, P2 appear in log).
  - Workers request and release resources; grants logged.
  - Program exits on its own (no hang).
  - Final statistics block printed.
  - t03.log created and non-empty.
Fail:  Hang, crash, no log file, missing statistics.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T04  IPC cleanup after normal exit
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Commands (run in sequence):
    ipcs -m | grep -c "0x47605"   # note count before (expect 0)
    ipcs -q | grep -c "0x47606"
    ./oss -n 3 -s 2 -t 2 -f /dev/null
    ipcs -m | grep -c "0x47605"   # expect 0 again
    ipcs -q | grep -c "0x47606"   # expect 0 again

Pass:  Both counts return 0 after the run.
Fail:  Non-zero counts — leaked shared memory or message queue.

Cleanup if leaked:
    ipcs -m                        # find shmid
    ipcs -q                        # find msqid
    ipcrm -m <shmid>
    ipcrm -q <msqid>


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T05  IPC cleanup after SIGINT (Ctrl-C)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Commands:
    ./oss -n 40 -s 10 -t 10 &
    sleep 2
    kill -INT $!
    wait $!
    ipcs -m | grep -c "0x47605"   # expect 0
    ipcs -q | grep -c "0x47606"   # expect 0

Pass:  Final statistics printed; IPC keys absent after kill.
Fail:  Leftover IPC segments or no statistics output.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T06  Simultaneous-process cap (-s and MAX_RUNNING=18)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Commands:
    ./oss -n 40 -s 5 -t 5 -f t06.log &
    # While running, check active count several times:
    sleep 1; ps aux | grep worker | grep -v grep | wc -l

Pass:  Worker count never exceeds 5 (s_limit) or 18 (hard cap).
Fail:  Worker count exceeds s_limit or 18.

Also verify in t06.log:
    grep "forked worker" t06.log | wc -l     # should equal n (up to 40 or 5-sec cap)


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T07  Wall-clock forking cap (5 real seconds)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Command:
    time ./oss -n 1000 -s 5 -t 3 -f t07.log

Pass:
  - Real wall time is roughly 5-8 seconds (5s fork window + drain).
  - "Total resource requests" in statistics > 0.
  - oss does not fork 1000 workers.
Fail:  Run takes > 60 seconds (not stopping), or forks thousands of workers.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T08  Custom log file
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Command:
    ./oss -n 3 -s 2 -t 2 -f mytest.log
    ls -l mytest.log
    head -5 mytest.log
    tail -5 mytest.log

Pass:
  - mytest.log exists and is non-empty.
  - First line contains "OSS started".
  - Last lines contain statistics.
  - Default oss.log is NOT created (or is unchanged if pre-existing).
Fail:  Log file missing, empty, or wrong file created.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T09  Log line cap (10,000 lines)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Command:
    ./oss -n 1000 -s 18 -t 10 -f t09.log
    wc -l t09.log

Pass:  Line count is <= ~10,100 (10,000 cap + table headers + statistics).
Fail:  Hundreds of thousands of lines (cap not enforced).


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T10  Blocking and unblocking (resource contention)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Command:
    ./oss -n 10 -s 8 -t 5 -f t10.log
    grep "not granted" t10.log | head -5
    grep "granting.*from freed" t10.log | head -5

Pass:
  - At least some "not granted, process blocked" entries exist.
  - At least some "granting P* (from freed resources)" entries exist
    (proves wait queues work correctly).
Fail:  No blocking ever occurs (unlikely with 8 workers and 50 resources),
       or no waiters ever get unblocked after being blocked.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T11  Deadlock detection and resolution
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Run with a high worker count and short time limit to increase deadlock odds:

Command:
    ./oss -n 30 -s 18 -t 8 -f t11.log
    grep -i "deadlock" t11.log

Pass:
  - "Master running deadlock detection" appears every ~1 sim-second.
  - When deadlock occurs: "Processes P* deadlocked" line present.
  - Followed by "Killing process P*" and resource release list.
  - Subsequent detection runs show fewer/no deadlocked processes.
  - "Processes terminated by deadlock" in statistics >= 1 (if deadlock occurred).
Fail:
  - No deadlock detection lines at all.
  - Program hangs after "deadlocked" message.
  - Statistics show 0 deadlock runs.

Note: Deadlock may not occur every run. If t11.log shows 0 kills but detection
ran, that is acceptable — it means no deadlock occurred in that particular run.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T12  Clock advances correctly (not frozen)
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Command:
    ./oss -n 5 -s 3 -t 5 -f t12.log
    grep "granting\|releasing\|blocked" t12.log | awk -F'time ' '{print $2}' | sort -u | head -20

Pass:  Timestamps are spread across many different values (not all identical).
       Events should span from ~0:100000000 through several simulated seconds.
Fail:  All events show the same timestamp (e.g., "1:960000000") — clock frozen.
       This was the original turn-flood bug; should be fixed with turn_sent.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T13  Statistics output completeness
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Command:
    ./oss -n 5 -s 3 -t 3 -f t13.log
    tail -8 t13.log

Pass:  Output contains all four statistics lines:
  "Total resource requests:"
  "Immediately granted:"      (with percentage)
  "Deadlock detection runs:"
  "Processes terminated by deadlock:"
Fail:  Any statistics line missing.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T14  Resource table format
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Command:
    ./oss -n 5 -s 3 -t 5 -f t14.log
    grep -A 15 "OSS Resource Table" t14.log | head -15

Pass:  Table has a header row (R0 R1 ... R9), an "Avail:" row, and one row
       per active process. Avail row values sum to <= 50 at all times.
Fail:  Table missing, malformed, or available + allocated > 50 for any resource.


────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
T15  No orphan processes after exit
────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Commands:
    ./oss -n 5 -s 3 -t 3 &
    wait
    ps aux | grep worker | grep -v grep

Pass:  No worker processes remain after oss exits.
Fail:  Orphaned worker processes still running.


